    "created_at": "2016-06-16T13:58:13Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-06-16T13:58:13Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "In terminal IPython, `!` calls `os.system`. It does make sense that `ls` and `echo` are available, because these are Windows executables added to PATH when you run git-bash, so they will work even in cmd subprocesses. You can see this by starting git-bash, then starting cmd inside git-bash. `ls`, `echo`, etc. all still work.\n\nWhere you will see the difference is bash builtins, such as `alias`, which do work in git-bash, don't work in cmd, and also don't work in IPython's `!alias`, which shows the `cmd` error for a missing command.\n\nSo while `!echo asdf` works, the path doesn't actually exist in the context where cmd runs for the pipe output, and it rightly shows that it cannot find the path specified.\n\nYou can see where `/tmp` actually is by looking at the output of `mount`, which looks something like:\n\n```\nC:/Program Files/Git on / type ntfs (binary,noacl,auto)\nC:/Program Files/Git/usr/bin on /bin type ntfs (binary,noacl,auto)\nC:/Users/You/AppData/Local/Temp/2 on /tmp type ntfs (binary,noacl,posix=0,usertemp)\nC: on /c type ntfs (binary,noacl,posix=0,user,noumount,auto)\n```\n\nAnd if you pipe to the real (Windows) path, it works:\n\n```\ntmp = \"C:/Users/You/AppData/Local/Temp/2/tmp.whatever\"\n!echo asdf > $tmp\n```\n\nThe gist is that git-bash only sort-of modifies your environment, so while some bashy things work in subprocesses of git-bash, not all of them do.\n"
